{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611128"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:08:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:08:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16198"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16198","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16198"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.55,0.05,0.1,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8889"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74596"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8889"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16198"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60088"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2333"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"10640"},{"type":"tags","id":"10651"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21156"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21158"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74596"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA woman presents two weeks after giving birth concerned about her milk supply. She reports her breasts initially felt very full but are now softer.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes normal changes in breast fullness during establishment of lactation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Breasts should remain firm and engorged throughout lactation","Breasts normally soften after initial engorgement","Breast fullness indicates oversupply requiring treatment","Breast softening always indicates insufficient milk production","Breast fullness should steadily increase over the first month"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIt is normal for breasts to \u003Cstrong\u003Esoften after initial engorgement\u003C/strong\u003E as milk supply regulates to match infant demand. This typically occurs around 2-3 weeks postpartum and does not indicate insufficient supply if the baby is feeding well and gaining weight appropriately.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreasts should remain firm and engorged throughout lactation\u003C/strong\u003E - Persistent engorgement is uncomfortable and can lead to complications\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreast fullness indicates oversupply requiring treatment\u003C/strong\u003E - Initial fullness is normal and usually self-resolves\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreast softening always indicates insufficient milk production\u003C/strong\u003E - Softening is a normal physiological change\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreast fullness should steadily increase over the first month\u003C/strong\u003E - Supply typically regulates downward after initial engorgement\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETrue insufficient milk supply is rare and usually related to anatomical or hormonal issues. Most concerns about supply arise during normal physiological changes in breast fullness.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Normal breast changes during lactation include initial engorgement followed by softening as supply regulates.","True insufficient milk supply is rare and usually related to inadequate glandular tissue development or hormonal issues.","Perceived insufficient milk supply is more common and often relates to normal physiological changes or improper feeding technique."],"references":["Spatz DL, Miller J. When Your Breasts Might Not Work: Anticipatory Guidance for Health-Care Professionals. J Perinat Educ. 2021 Jan 1;30(1):13-18. doi: 10.1891/J-PE-D-20-00014. Epub 2020 Dec 28. PMID: 33488043; PMCID: PMC7819476.","Alekseev NP, Vladimir II, Nadezhda TE. Pathological postpartum breast engorgement: prediction, prevention, and resolution. Breastfeed Med. 2015 May;10(4):203-8. doi: 10.1089/bfm.2014.0047. Epub 2015 Mar 16. PMID: 25774443; PMCID: PMC4410447.","Mangesi L, Zakarija-Grkovic I. Treatments for breast engorgement during lactation. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2016 Jun 28;2016(6):CD006946. doi: 10.1002/14651858.CD006946.pub3. Update in: Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2020 Sep 18;9:CD006946. doi: 10.1002/14651858.CD006946.pub4. PMID: 27351423; PMCID: PMC7388926.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60088"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16198"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60088"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T18:36:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T07:59:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8889"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74596"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type